	<div id="help-links">
		<h4>Basics</h4>
		<p>To make any text, or an image, into a link, select it with the mouse (for text, click and drag the cursor to select all the text you want to make into a link), then click the link button (<img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/toolbar-buttons/link-button.gif" style="vertical-align: bottom;" alt="Link button">) in the toolbar.</p>
		<p>To edit an existing link, click on the text or image that is already linked and then click the link button (<img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/toolbar-buttons/link-button.gif" style="vertical-align: bottom;" alt="Link button">) in the toolbar.</p>
		<p>To remove a link without deleting the content, click on the text or image that is linked and then click the unlink button (<img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/toolbar-buttons/unlink-button.gif" style="vertical-align: bottom;" alt="Unlink button">) in the toolbar.</p>
		<h4>The Link Dialog</h4>
		<p>When you click the toolbar button to add or edit a link, you will be presented with this dialog:</p>
		<p style="text-align: center"><img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/link-dialog.gif" alt="Link Dialog"></p>
		<p>You can insert a link from this dialog in several ways:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Type or Paste URL</strong><br>
				Type the URL in manually, or copy and paste it. This is necessary if creating a link to an external website - you need to put in the full URL starting with "http://"</li>
			<li><strong>Select from the Link List</strong><br>
				<img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/link-list-dropdown.gif" alt="Link list example"><br>
				To insert a link to another page of the site, or another internal resource, click on the link-list drop-down and select the desired item. This will insert a special link that will automatically update properly if the page or item is renamed.</li>
			<li><img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/browse-button.gif" alt="Browse for media" style="vertical-align: middle;"> <strong>Browse for a File</strong><br>
				Clicking the browse button will open a dialog to the file manager, where you can upload files from your computer and select one to use for the link. See the "File Manager" help tab above for more information.</li>
		</ul>
		<h4>Other Options</h4>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Target</strong><br>
				Optionally choose how you want the link to open - in the same window, or a new one. The default is to open in the same window.</li>
			<li><strong>Title</strong><br>
				Optionally set title text. This will appear in a tooltip when you mouse over the link, and will be picked up by search engines and screen readers. You should always set a title for image links to help the user know where it will take them.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
	<div id="help-images">
		<h4>Basics</h4>
		<p>To insert an image, place the text cursor where you want to insert the image and click the image button (<img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/toolbar-buttons/image-button.gif" style="vertical-align: bottom;" alt="Image button">) in the toolbar.</p>
		<p>To update an existing image, click on the image to select it then click the image button (<img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/toolbar-buttons/image-button.gif" style="vertical-align: bottom;" alt="Image button">) in the toolbar.</p>
		<h4>The Image Dialog</h4>
		<p>When you click the toolbar button to insert or update an image, you will be presented with this dialog:</p>
		<p style="text-align: center"><img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/image-dialog.gif" alt="Image Dialog"></p>
		<p>You can insert an image in one of two ways:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Type or Paste URL</strong><br>
				Type the URL in manually, or copy and paste it, if the image you want to insert is from another website. Note that the owner of the other website will not likely appreciate you linking to their image directly. It's better to download a copy and upload it to your site - making sure you are not violating any copyrights.</li>
			<li><img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/browse-button.gif" alt="Browse for media" style="vertical-align: middle;"> <strong>Browse for a File</strong><br>
				Clicking the browse button will open a dialog to the file manager, where you can upload images from your computer and select one to use. See the "File Manager" help tab above for more information.</li>
		</ul>
		<h4>Other Options</h4>
		<ul>
			<li><strong>Image Description</strong><br>
				This provides search engines and screen readers with a description of the image. It also appears as a tooltip to users when they mouse over the image, except when the image is a link, in which case the link title will be used as the tooltip instead.<br><br>We recommended always filling this out as accurately as you can.</li>
			<li><strong>Alignment</strong><br>
				Optionally select the way the image should be aligned in relation to the text.</li>
			<li><strong>Dimensions</strong><br>
				It is best to always leave this field blank. If you set the dimensions of the image, the web browser will make sure the image is displayed at the specified size, which can produce bad results such as stretching/pixelating. Leaving this blank will display the image in it's native size. If you are using the Biscuit File Manager, you will be able to choose among the available default image sizes, so you can choose the one that best fits. You can also pre-size the image before you upload it to ensure that it will appear in the right size when you insert it. In addition, you can ask your web developer to setup some pre-set image sizes that you will commonly want to use. These will then be available to choose from in the Biscuit File Manager. Please contact your web developer to discuss this option or get more detailed help with image sizing.</li>
			<li><strong>Border</strong><br>
				Optionally set the size of border you want applied to the image. The border colour will always be black.</li>
			<li><strong>Vertical and Horizontal space</strong><br>
				Setting values in these fields will add margin to the top and bottom (vertical) or sides (horizontal) of the image. Note that these margins may get overridden by the theme your web developer programmed. If that's the case, please contact your developer for help with how to add spacing around images.</li>
		</ul>
		<p><strong>Note:</strong> In addition to the border and spacing options available in the image dialog, you can ask your developer to provide you with special custom styles, if desired, that you can apply to images by selecting them from the "Styles" drop-down in the editor toolbar. For example, if you want some images to have a coloured border, or you want to be able to apply several style/layout options with a single click. Contact your developer if you are interested in such options.</p>
	</div>
	<div id="help-pasting">
		<p>Most content that you copy from somewhere else can simply be pasted into the Tiny MCE editor using the normal paste keyboard shortcut (CTRL-V in Windows, CMD-V in Mac OS). However, if you copied the content from a source that is not plain text, such as another website or a word processor like Microsoft Word, the styles from the source content may get pasted as well. This can interfere with your website's styles by introducing inconsistencies that can range from a minor annoyance to a major breakage.</p>
		<p>To work around this problem, there are two special paste buttons in the toolbar:</p>
		<ul>
			<li><img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/toolbar-buttons/paste-from-word.gif" alt="Paste from Word" style="vertical-align: middle;"> <strong>Paste from Word</strong><br>
				Clicking this button opens a special dialog with a text box into which you can paste the content you copied from Microsoft Word. After pasting, while most Word styles will have been removed there may still be some unwanted coding from Word. You can easily remove this, as well as tidy up the formatting a bit, in the dialog before you insert the text into your content.<br>
				<img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/paste-from-word-dialog.gif" alt="Paste from word"></li>
			<li><img src="/extensions/tiny_mce/images/help/toolbar-buttons/paste-as-plain-text.gif" alt="Paste as Plain Text" style="vertical-align: middle;"> <strong>Paste as Plain Text</strong><br>
				When you click on this button, the normal paste function will switch to plain text mode. You will be notified of this when you click the button. Once the button is highlighted, anything you paste will be pasted as plain text with any of it's original styling removed. This is the best option to use if you are copying and pasting content from another web page. When you have finished using plain text paste mode, click the button again to switch back to normal paste mode.</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
